               <p>SECOND COUNT, stating it to be the property of 
               
                  <persName id="t18310908-316-victim2284" type="victimName">
                     Thomas 
                     Smith
                  <interp inst="t18310908-316-victim2284" type="surname" value="Smith"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-316-victim2284" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-316-victim2284" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-316-person2285">
                  THOMAS 
                  SMITH
               <interp inst="t18310908-316-person2285" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-316-person2285" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-316-person2285" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I <rs id="t18310908-316-viclabel1628" type="occupation">drive the Wantage waggon</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310908-316-victim2284 t18310908-316-viclabel1628"></join> - the prisoner was in my service, and used to assist me in driving, On the 23rd of August I had two purses, containing 20 half-crowns, 20 shillings, 20 sixpences, and three 5l. Bank notes; they were all in a bag in the waggon - he walked away in the night, without saying any thing to me, which gave me suspicion - I got into the waggon, and missed the bag, money,<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183109080137"></xptr>and notes; I spoke to Dunner, the patrol, and he brought the prisoner to me in the course of the night.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-316-person2286">
                  SAMUEL 
                  DUNNER
               <interp inst="t18310908-316-person2286" type="surname" value="DUNNER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-316-person2286" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-316-person2286" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Bow-street patrol. Smith gave me information, and I found the prisoner near the ten mile-stone on the Staines road; the waggon was going the contrary direction - he said he had not been with the waggon at all, that he had been up the road with four baskets, and was then returning home; I found on him the two purses and the silver - I could not find the notes, and he denied having them; I took him back, and met the prosecutor - I then stripped the prisoner, and he took the three 5l. notes out of his bosom; here are the notes, the bag, and the money.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-316-person2287">
                  THOMAS 
                  SMITH
               <interp inst="t18310908-316-person2287" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-316-person2287" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-316-person2287" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . This purse is mine, and I believe the notes also.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. He gave me the notes out of the waggon, told me to walk on, and I should meet him at Colnbrook the next morning.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18310908-316-verdict1629" type="verdictDescription">
